\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

 is involved)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It works both for square and rectangular matrices but the number of columns
 of the left matrix must be equal to the number of rows of the second matrix
 (
\emph on
conformable
\emph default
 matrices).
 Inner dimensions must coincide: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m\times n\right)\cdot\left(i\times j\right)$
\end_inset

 gives a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times j$
\end_inset

 only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is not limited to 2-D matrices but it is generalized to n-dimensions:
 
