x & =V_{d}t\\
x & =V_{b}\left(t-T_{gps}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{b}$
\end_inset

 are the speeds of the dolphin and the boat (8 and 10 m/s, respectively).
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{gps}$
\end_inset

 is the time needed to set the GPS (2 min = 120 s) and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,\ t$
\end_inset

 are the unknowns, the distance and the time of the encounter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One can solve this by substitution of variables as you learned at high school,
 but linear algebra is much more effective.
 The equations can be written in terms of vectors and one transformation
 matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
x-V_{d}t & =0\\
x-V_{b}t & =-V_{b}T_{gps}
\end{cases}\Rightarrow\begin{bmatrix}1 & -V_{d}\\
1 & -V_{b}
\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}x\\
t
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\
-V_{b}T_{gps}
\end{bmatrix}\Rightarrow\mathbf{Ax}=\mathbf{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

